04195nam a22006975i 9780226457468DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264574687 a10.7208/97802264574682doi  a(DE-B1597)523897  a(OCoLC)979417511  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aSCI0000002bisacsh  aHL 10042rvk1 aMorgan, Benjamin, eauthor.14aThe Outward Mind :bMaterialist Aesthetics in Victorian Science and Literature /cBenjamin Morgan. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b30 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Materialist Aesthetics -- tPart One: Toward a Science of Beauty -- tPart Two: The Outward Turn -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThough underexplored in contemporary scholarship, the Victorian attempts to turn aesthetics into a science remain one of the most fascinating aspects of that era. In The Outward Mind, Benjamin Morgan approaches this period of innovation as an important origin point for current attempts to understand art or beauty using the tools of the sciences. Moving chronologically from natural theology in the early nineteenth century to laboratory psychology in the early twentieth, Morgan draws on little-known archives of Victorian intellectuals such as William Morris, Walter Pater, John Ruskin, and others to argue that scientific studies of mind and emotion transformed the way writers and artists understood the experience of beauty and effectively redescribed aesthetic judgment as a biological adaptation. Looking beyond the Victorian period to humanistic critical theory today, he also shows how the historical relationship between science and aesthetics could be a vital resource for rethinking key concepts in contemporary literary and cultural criticism, such as materialism, empathy, practice, and form. At a moment when the tumultuous relationship between the sciences and the humanities is the subject of ongoing debate, Morgan argues for the importance of understanding the arts and sciences as incontrovertibly intertwined.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aAestheticsxPsychological aspects. 0aAesthetics, Britishy19th century. 0aArtsxPsychological aspects. 0aAuthors, Englishy19th centuryxAesthetics. 0aMaterialismzEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aNeuroanthropology. 4aAlexander Bain. 4aJohn Ruskin. 4aVernon Lee. 4aWalter Pater. 4aWilliam Morris. 4aaffect. 4aempathy. 4aform. 4amaterialism. 4aphysiological aesthetics. 70(DE-601)1043939980(DE-588)4066562-8aWissenschaft2gnd 70(DE-601)1044703480(DE-588)4125698-0aKultur2gnd 70(DE-601)1057224130(DE-588)4127749-1aMaterialismus2gnd 70(DE-601)1064005410(DE-588)4000626-8aÄsthetik2gnd 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226457468423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226457468.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles